.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.sp
These subroutines generate graphic output commands for processing with
the \fIplot(1)\fP plotting filters. They are slightly more general than
those in \fIlibplot\fP as these take a file pointer.  They also include
the BRL 3\-D extensions to the plot intermediate code.
.sp
\fIPl_space\fP or \fIpl_3space\fP must be used before any of the graphic
primitives to declare the amount of space necessary. See \fIplot3(5)\fP.
.sp
\fIPl_box\fP or \fIpl_3box\fP draws a box between the two given opposite
points. The \(aqpen\(aq will be left at the second point.
.sp
\fIPl_circle\fP draws a circle of radius \fIr\fP with center at the point
(\fIx\fP, \fIy\fP). Note that \fIcircle\fP and \fIarc\fP cannot be transformed in
three space if one is using a filter to do that.
.sp
\fIPl_arc\fP draws an arc of a circle with center at the point (\fIx\fP, \fIy\fP)
between the points (\fIx0\fP, \fIy0\fP) and (\fIx1\fP, \fIy1\fP).
.sp
String arguments to \fIpl_label\fP and \fIpl_linmod\fP are terminated by nulls
and do not contain new\-lines.
.sp
There are also 2\-D and 3_D double\-precision versions, with arguments
identical to their counterparts above.  The naming conventions are to
change the prefix to "pd"; examples are thus \fIpd_point\fP and
\fIpd_3point\fP. Vector versions for 3_D (also double\-precision) are
prefixed "pdv", as in \fIpdv_3point\fP.
.sp
See \fIplot3(5)\fP and \fIplot(5)\fP for a description of the effect of the
remaining functions.
